{{Unreferenced|date=December 2009}} {{Infobox song contest entry | song = {{Flagicon|Greece}} "Clown" | image = | caption = | year = 1988 | country = Greece | artist = [[Afroditi Frida]] | as = | with = | language = Greek | languages = | composer = Dimitris Saksilis | lyricist = Dimitris Saksilis | conductor = Haris Andreadis | place = 17th | points = 10 | lyrics = [http://www.diggiloo.net/?1988gr from Diggiloo Thrush] | clip = | prev = Stop | prev_link = Stop (Bang song) | next = To diko sou asteri | next_link = To diko sou asteri }}
'''"Clown"''' ([[Greek alphabet|Greek script]]: '''"Κλόουν"''') was the [[Greece|Greek]] entry in the [[Eurovision Song Contest 1988]], performed in [[Greek language|Greek]] by [[Afroditi Frida]]. It is generally regarded as the country's most embarrassing Eurovision entry in the history of the competition as of 2018.
The song was performed fourteenth on the night, following [[Denmark]]'s [[Hot Eyes|Kirsten & Søren]] with "[[Ka' du se hva' jeg sa'?]]" and preceding [[Norway]]'s [[Karoline Krüger]] with "[[For vår jord]]". At the close of voting, it had received 10 points, placing 17th in a field of 21.
The song is sung from the perspective of a [[clown]], with Frida expressing her joy at amusing others. She sings, however, that "I have a heart" and makes mention of the fact that she is required to be positive in her job even when she does not feel that way.
It was succeeded as [[Greece in the Eurovision Song Contest|Greek representative]] at the [[Eurovision Song Contest 1989|1989 Contest]] by [[Mariana Efstratiou|Mariana]] with "[[To Diko Sou Asteri]]".
