The '''National Archives of Guinea''' were established in the 1960s<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Klein|first=Martin|date=1981|title=Report on Archives of the Popular and Revolutionary Republic of Guinea in Conakry|url=|journal=History in Africa|volume=9|pages=333-334|via=https://www.jstor.org/stable/3171527}}</ref> after [[Guinea|the country]] gained its independence. They have been moved three times since then and are currently situated in the capital city of [[Conakry]].<ref name=Graeme>{{cite journal |last=Counsel |first=Graeme |year=2009 |title=Archival and Research Resources in Conakry, Guinea |journal=History in Africa |publisher=Cambridge University Press |volume=36 |pages=439–445 |jstor=40864528|language=English}}</ref> <!--RELEVANT? In 2007, the archives occupied two rooms of [[Fourah Bay College]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-leone-krios-idUSL0684532820070910 |title=Krio heritage rich but crumbling in Sierra Leone |author=Daniel Flynn |date=9 September 2007 |publisher=[[Reuters]]}}</ref>--> As of around 1995, the archives had a collection of over 3,000 volumes.<ref name="Inc1995">{{cite book|author=Gale Research Inc|title=Worldmark Encyclopedia of the Nations: Africa|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=GzQEAQAAIAAJ|accessdate=16 March 2011|year=1995|publisher=Gale Research|isbn=978-0-8103-9880-1|page=189}}</ref>

