{{operational plan | name = Operation ''Boswilger'' | partof = the [[South African Border War]] | image = | caption = | scope = | type = | location = Angola | coordinates = {{Location map many | Angola | width = 260 | float = right | label = Chitado | pos = top | marksize = 6 | lat_deg = -17.3227 | lon_deg = 13.9211 | label2 = Ondangwa | pos2 = right | mark2size = 6 | lat2_deg = -17.55 | lon2_deg = 15.57 }} | planned = | planned_by = | objective = Hot pursuit operation against PLAN insurgents. | target = | date = 29–30 June 1985 | time = | time-begin = | time-end = | timezone = | executed_by = | outcome = | casualties = | fatalities = | injuries = }} {{Campaignbox South African Border War}}
'''Operation ''Boswilger''''' ({{lang-en|Operation Bush Willow}}) was a [[military operation]] executed by the [[South West Africa Territorial Force]] (SWATF) in June 1985 during the [[South African Border War]] and [[Angolan Civil War]]. The SADF soldiers pursued [[SWAPO|SWAPO's]], [[People's Liberation Army of Namibia|PLAN]] insurgents, who had attacked infrastructure, out of South West Africa/Namibia across the border into Angola.
==Background== On 28 June, PLAN insurgents entered South West Africa damaging a bridge between Epali and [[Ondangwa]], sabotaging twenty telephone poles, mortaring the [[Eenhana]] SADF base and a bomb was detonated at the Ongwediva Teachers Training College<ref name=Steenkamp>{{cite book|last=Steenkamp|first=Willem|title=South Africa's border war, 1966-1989|year=1989|publisher=Ashanti Pub.|location=Gibraltar|isbn=0620139676}}</ref>{{rp|132}} No one was injured in these attacks.<ref name="Heitman01">{{Cite book |title=Mobility Conquers: The Story of 61 Mechanised Battalion Group 1978-2005 |last=Steenkamp |first=Willem |last2=Heitman |first2=Helmoed-Romer |publisher=Helion and Company |year=2016 |isbn=978-1911096528}}</ref>{{rp|691}}
On 29 June 1985, [[South West African Territorial Force|South West Africa Territory Force]] (SWATF) mechanised reaction teams set off in a hot pursuit operation following the tracks. Orders had been given by Brigadier [[Joep Joubert]], to follow the insurgents even if they crossed back into Angola.<ref name=Heitman01/>{{rp|691}} Bases were attacked up to 40&nbsp;km inside Angola. There was twenty-three contacts in the first day killing forty-three insurgents and thirteen contacts and another fourteen insurgents killed on the second day.<ref name=Heitman01/>{{rp|691}} The operation lasted two days before the SWATF withdrew back across the border to SWA.<ref name=Heitman01/>{{rp|691}}
At the end of the operation, 56 PLAN insurgents had been killed with one dead from the SWATF with large amounts of weapons and ammunition captured.<ref name=Steenkamp/>{{rp|132}}
==Aftermath== Later South African Foreign Minister [[Pik Botha]] would justify the operation to cross the border into Angola as the Angolan's had failed to prevent the incursions of SWAPO's insurgents into South West Africa/Namibian territory, as prescribed by the [[Lusaka Accords]].<ref name=Heitman01/>{{rp|692}}
